<header class="header">
  <h1>Do You Have Enough Growing Degree Days for Winter Squash?</h1>
  <p class="tagline">
    Winter squash maturity depends on sustained heat before 32°F returns.
  </p>
  <p class="lede">
    In a typical year, first frost at <strong>32°F (0°C)</strong> defines the seasonal deadline for winter squash.
    Because winter squash is a long-season crop, whether it matures depends heavily
    on how many Growing Degree Days (GDD) accumulate before frost returns.
  </p>
</header>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Start With Your First Frost Boundary</h2>

  <p>
    GrowByDate uses 1991–2020 climate normals and frames frost timing at the
    <strong>50% probability level</strong>.
    That means your listed first frost date represents a typical-year planning anchor —
    not an exact prediction.
  </p>

  <p>
    You can determine your seasonal frost window using the
    <a href="/tools/first-frost-planner/">First Frost Planner</a>.
  </p>

  <p>
    That date defines the maturity deadline for frost-sensitive crops like winter squash.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Winter Squash Has High Heat Requirements</h2>

  <p>
    Winter squash varieties — including butternut, acorn, and kabocha types —
    require sustained warmth for fruit development and ripening.
  </p>

  <p>
    Most calculations use a base temperature of <strong>50°F (10°C)</strong>.
  </p>

  <pre>
GDD = ((Daily High + Daily Low) ÷ 2) − 50
  </pre>

  <p>
    Because squash fruits must fully mature and cure on the vine,
    consistent heat accumulation is critical.
  </p>

  <p>
    You can estimate your seasonal heat budget using the
    <a href="/tools/growing-degree-day-planner/">Growing Degree Day Planner</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Typical GDD Requirements for Winter Squash</h2>

  <p>
    While exact needs vary by variety, winter squash often requires:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Early varieties:</strong> ~1,400–1,600 GDD</li>
    <li><strong>Standard varieties:</strong> ~1,600–1,800+ GDD</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Some long-season varieties may require even more accumulated heat.
  </p>

  <p class="fine">
    Exact values vary by cultivar and local growing conditions.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>When You Likely Have Enough Heat</h2>

  <p>
    Winter squash is more likely to mature reliably if:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>Your seasonal GDD comfortably exceeds 1,600–1,800.</li>
    <li>Summer temperatures remain consistently warm.</li>
    <li>You select earlier-maturing varieties in borderline climates.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    In climates with strong summer heat,
    even moderate frost-free windows may support squash maturity.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>When Heat Is Likely Insufficient</h2>

  <p>
    Winter squash is at higher risk if:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>Your seasonal GDD remains below ~1,500.</li>
    <li>Nighttime temperatures are consistently cool.</li>
    <li>You select long-season varieties in short climates.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    As explained in
    <a href="/guides/why-days-to-maturity-isnt-enough-in-cold-climates/">Why Days to Maturity Isn’t Enough in Cold Climates</a>,
    calendar days alone often overstate feasibility in cooler regions.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Risk Margin Matters</h2>

  <p>
    Because frost timing is probability-based,
    some years may accumulate slightly more or less heat than average.
  </p>

  <p>
    If your seasonal GDD barely matches a variety’s requirement,
    maturity becomes more sensitive to summer temperature variation.
  </p>

  <p>
    A strong heat surplus improves reliability.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Improving Your Chances</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>Choose early-maturing squash varieties.</li>
    <li>Plant promptly after frost risk drops.</li>
    <li>Use the warmest, most sun-exposed part of your garden.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    For broader climate modeling context, see
    <a href="/guides/how-frost-dates-and-growing-degree-days-work-together/">How Frost Dates and Growing Degree Days Work Together</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>The Winter Squash Feasibility Model</h2>

  <p>
    Evaluating winter squash maturity follows this sequence:
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>First Frost Date → Seasonal GDD → Variety Requirement → Risk Margin</strong>
  </p>

  <p>
    When accumulated heat exceeds crop demand,
    squash can mature and cure properly in a typical year.
  </p>

  <p>
    When it does not, fruit may remain immature at first frost.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Summary</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>Winter squash is sensitive to frost at 32°F.</li>
    <li>Frost dates are framed at 50% probability using climate normals.</li>
    <li>Most winter squash requires 1,400–1,800+ Growing Degree Days.</li>
    <li>Strong heat accumulation improves maturity reliability.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    In short or cool climates, winter squash success depends on whether
    your seasonal heat budget exceeds the crop’s thermal demand.
  </p>
</section>